name: Claire Jones
tweet: @hatsopotatso @LiamThorpECHO Yes, Allerton Rd and Aigburth Rd both subpar. I accept Liam didn't mean anything by choosing this shop rather than, say, Waitrose in Formby. It just hit a nerve. I haven't been to the Speke store, which sounds first rate, so maybe that's why I read too much into it.

name: Claire Jones
tweet: @BornToBeScouse @LiamThorpECHO Yes, I need to relax a bit. I am fearful that the anti vaccination campaign is, like Brexit and Trumpism, a lot more mainstream than we think — and that calling people stupid will make it more so. But who knows what drives it. Probably not one tweet, as you say.

name: Claire Jones
tweet: @Frailerpark @LiamThorpECHO Yes, my mum lives not far from there. It just jarred with me. But I take Liam’s (and others) point, I may have read too much into it and had a sense of humour failure.

name: Claire Jones
tweet: @Frailerpark @LiamThorpECHO I don’t like that this sentiment is portrayed as a phenomenon confined to one income group. It’s not true. Think of MMR debate for instance. I accept that this isn’t what Liam was getting at though.

name: Claire Jones
tweet: @Frailerpark @LiamThorpECHO In what sense?

name: Claire Jones
tweet: @hemdow @LiamThorpECHO I’d add that this wave of anti-vaccine sentiment is happening across western democracies. Even places seen as handling the pandemic well, such as Germany. It’s alarming.

name: Claire Jones
tweet: @hemdow @LiamThorpECHO I can imagine. But I think his column on the protests, which appealed to a sense of community and support of the NHS, is exactly the sort of piece that can win round people who are more ambivalent about vaccines and lockdowns. They might not comment, but they will be influenced.

name: Claire Jones
tweet: @hemdow @LiamThorpECHO I think a lot of people are ambivalent about vaccination and that labeling them all idiots will lead to a broader backlash and lack of herd immunity. But I’ve picked a poor forum to make this point. I can see the protests have caused a lot of upset and sown division. Nasty.

name: Claire Jones
tweet: @hemdow @LiamThorpECHO The abuse from the protesters is no doubt vile, no one ought to accept and it is nice of you to show solidarity.

name: Claire Jones
tweet: Great reporting from @GuyChazan and @ErikaSolomon on vaccine production/ logistics

name: Claire Jones
tweet: @abi_carey @LiamThorpECHO  https://t.co/lQg6c2ztz2

name: Claire Jones
tweet: @BornToBeScouse @LiamThorpECHO I disagree. He is one of the most prominent and well respected reporters covering an important city. That doesn’t make you POTUS, but there’s power there.

name: Claire Jones
tweet: @vCEO @LiamThorpECHO Yes. It’s the shift from ambivalence to dead set against that I find alarming. There is still a big group that I suspect are ambivalent and could still be convinced though.

name: Claire Jones
tweet: @LiamThorpECHO Fair enough, it just didn’t sound great IMO. But I appreciate it was an off the cuff tweet and we’re all entitled to those. And I do feel for you having to cover the protests, that must be tough.

name: Claire Jones
tweet: @PlanetSpurge @LiamThorpECHO It’s Home AND Bargain. What’s wrong with you all?

name: Claire Jones
tweet: @vCEO @LiamThorpECHO Yes, which is what Liam’s reporting does very well. What I am troubled by is how widespread anti-vaccine sentiment is. It goes way beyond fringe groups:  https://t.co/6vSZoIvYOn.

name: Claire Jones
tweet: @BornToBeScouse @LiamThorpECHO Clearly it isn’t. And I appreciate the frustration, personal and professional, when you have to go and report on the protests. That must be tough. I am concerned that we don’t give the likes of Sine Missione more of a fan base, though.

name: Claire Jones
tweet: @LiamThorpECHO The Speke thing also wound me up to be honest. Bit snooty to suggest that anti-vaccine sentiment is confined to people who are less well off.

name: Claire Jones
tweet: @LiamThorpECHO Fair enough. My point’s more that it’s inaccurate to portray all those with concerns about taking the vaccine as conspiracy theorists. Many have concerns about the pace at which candidates have been developed, for instance. Better to engage with them, than focus on name calling.
